@node "Introduction" "Introduction"

@{MS "Introduction"}

A hardware track display is very useful, if you need it! The most time this type of hardware is only
good for lighting up the room!@{par}

This will be changed when using TrackDisplayClock! TrackDisplayClock displays the system time on
your track display! Its cool, its useful and of cource the time is always in visual range.@{par}

Delete all programs using screens, windows or icons to display the time and of course donÇt forget
to remove your noclick tool! TrackDisplayClock is doing all these jobs and your system will be
faster than before! (-8@{par}

I had the idea of making such program years ago, but that time I only wrote a little experimental
program wich switched off the system. A few days ago I decided to create this tiny tool, to find out
how many unused track displays are working out there!

@endnode
@node "Systemrequirements" "Systemrequirements"

@{MS "System requirements"}

TrackDisplayClock (should work) works on all Amigas with OS 2.0 or higher.@{par}

Also required is an Amiga with TrackDisplay and and some time so display! (-8

@endnode
@node "Featurelist" "Features"

@{MS "Features"}

¯ Commodity@{par}

¯ Online Help@{par}

¯ 100% Assembler@{par}

¯ Locale Support@{par}

@endnode
@node "Distribution" "Distribution"

@{MS "Distribution"}

This program should be published on every public medium, as long as all files in the archive are
unchanged. If this medium is a CD I expect a free copy. (AminetCDs excluded)@{par}

@{b}TrackDisplayClock is Mailware.@{ub}@{par}

I expect from everybody, who uses TrackDisplayClock regularly, to send me an email or postcard. I
think this does not hurt anybody, and I will have more fun to integrate new features.@{par}

@{b}I am not liable for injures or data loss caused by TrackDisplayClock! The use of
TrackDisplayClock is on your own responsibility !!!@{ub}

@endnode
@node "HowToInstall" "How to install TrackDisplayClock"

@{MS "How to install TrackDisplayClock"}

Just drag TrackDisplayClock into your WBstartup drawer and use the GUI or Tooltypes to configurate!@{par}

Thats all!

@endnode
@node "History" "History"

@{MS "History"}

This text is telling the story of TrackDisplayClock like a diary.

 @{MC "V1.00"}

First version.

 @{MC "V1.01"}

Small manual changes.

 @{MC "V1.02"}

Uncounted small changes.

 @{MC "V1.03"}

Used OnlineHelp module.

 @{MC "V1.04"}

Used new commodity module.

 @{MC "V1.05"}

@{"hotkey for quick disk access" link "MASTDeAc"} implemented.

 @{MC "V1.06"}

Again some bugfixes.

 @{MC "V1.07"}

Removed some unused modules.

 @{MC "V1.08"}

Some manual changes and improvments.

 @{MC "V1.09"}

BUGFIX: A mistake within the Commodity_AddObject routine caused that hotkey werenÇt filtered.

 @{MC "V1.10"}

Small catalog changes.

 @{MC "V1.11"}

BUGFIX: A bug caused TDC to write into random memory. This bug effected only chipmem (my system
default font), but now its seems to be fixed.@{par}
Manual reformated!

 @{MC "V1.12"}

FEATURE: Replaced the trackdisk.device hack by a system conform version.

 @{MC "V1.13"}

CHANGED: Reworked the whole clock handling.@{par}
FEATURE: Turbo time setup! Now the clock reset is as fast as possible! Required a little more
programming, but it looks better now!

 @{MC "V1.14"}

BUGFIX: The @{"CX Pri" link "MASTCXPr"} gadget wasnÇt working correct.

 @{MC "V1.15"}

BUGFIX: The online help failed on some gadgets.

 @{MC "V1.16"}

BUGFIX: Fixed a small GUI problem.

 @{MC "V1.17"}

BUGFIX: New system module fixes several GUI problems.

 @{MC "V1.18"}

BUGFIX: Compliled with new system module.

@endnode
